January 1, 1996   

COBALT TO STAY AROUND $30/LB NEAR TERM--DRI

DRI-McGraw-Hill has revised upward its projection for 1996 cobalt prices to
some extent, but remains bearish for the longer term. While DRI states that
markets now appear to remain in deficit through most of 1996, for the
longer term, it expects African production will rebound. New production
from a number of sources will impact the markets slowly, in all likelihood
not until 1998, with the strongest effect in 1999. ``This additional
material will close the gap between production and consumption and could
throw markets into a surplus,'' DRI said, adding: ``As a result of the new
supplies, prices are now forecast to fall across 1998 and 1999.''

