PHARMACEUTICAL BUSINESS NEWS via NewsNet
January 17, 1996

BRAZILIAN DRUG SALES UP28 PER CENT

Figures released in December by Brazil's association of pharmaceuticals
manufacturers (Abifarma - Associacao Brasileira da Industria
Farmaceutica), show 1995 sales rose 28.2 per cent to R$8.23 billion
Brazilian Reals (c US$8.35 billion). Brazil is the world's fourth
largest pharmaceuticals market after the US, France and Italy.

Only 50 per cent of Brazil's medicines production was exported in 1995
but Abifarma plans to raise this amount to between 10 per cent and 15
per cent with target markets being the South American Common Market
(Marcosur) and other Latin American countries.

During the year 1.77 billion units were sold, 16.4 per cent more than
in 1994. Abifarma's president Sr Jose Eduardo Bandeira de Mello said at
least five pharmaceutical companies were closing their plants in other
countries and planning to move their operations to Brazil.

In 1995, he said, laboratories invested $250 million in Brazil, up 25
per cent on the previous year. In 1996 he expected these investments to
increase substantially seeing Glaxo Wellcome alone was investing $111
million.



