MEDICINES MONITORING UNIT TO EXPAND POST MARKETING WORK

Following six years of successful development, The Medicines Monitoring
Unit (MEMO) based at Ninewells Hospital, Dundee, UK is to expand its
work, according to a report published in the current issue of the
journal Pharmaceutical Medicine (9:  177-184). The unit, which is
supported by the UK Medicines Control Agency, has developed an
automated database on record-linkage techniques to conduct post-
marketing drug safety studies, and currently has access to data for
400,000 residents of Tayside Scotland. In future, record linkage
studies will be conducted on the entire population of Scotland (5.5
million) giving the unit enhanced capacity to study newly-marketed
drugs. Other planned developments include linkage with GP-based
computer systems, and ISDN links to pharmacies (enabling the provision
of accurate drug utilisation data).



